This was one of the worst experiences I've had at a restaurant! We went for brunch on Sunday, party of 4. The space is extremely right. Granted, we expected a wait at any restaurant being Sunday afternoon. The host told us the wait was an hour, so we went to the place across the street since it was bigger and less crowded to get out of waiting in the cold. My friend kept going back to check in on the progress. She even told him 10 more minutes, "I'm putting a table together for you all." Which wasn't true/didn't happen. She went from 1 hour to 2 hours. She also failed to mention that brunch was over at 3pm. I only found out because I asked the bartender if we can take a look at the menu to decide what to order before sitting down since we had already waited just over 1 1/2 hrs. Their lunch menu is very limited so we decided to leave. We only went to try this place because of all the hype we heard from word of mouth. We just wish we would've been told when their brunch was over so we could've gone elsewhere. Definitely not worth the hype and we'll not be coming back.
No comment

Came here for brunch on Sunday and had a party of six.  We arrived at 10:30AM expecting an hour wait especially with such a large party and we were pleasantly surprised when we were told that our table was ready after only 30 minutes. While we waited outside I was surprised to see people eating outdoors in 45 degree weather with a stiff breeze.  Once inside we were seated and our waitress immediately took drink orders and gave us adequate time to look over our menus before taking our orders.  Our group had the Ricotta Pancakes, Mushroom Toast, Moroccan Scramble and Sage Scrambled Egg Panini. Everything was very good.  Portions were decent size except for the Sage Scrambled Egg Panini which was smallish.  The Ricotta Pancakes were as good as everyone said they would be.  The honeycomb butter was amazing.  The Mushroom Toast had a generous amount of sautéed maitake mushrooms and kale with a delicious brown wine sauce toppped with a beautifully poached egg. Delicious. Oh, and their coffee is also very good.  We enjoyed our meal and never felt rushed despite the people waiting outside. Would definitely recommend this place.
No comment
No comment
Hash browns were ok. The avocado they gave me had gone bad, and the fat on the bacon was not rendered and inedible. Check please.

You know what the food was good , and I liked the staff, they were all very sweet . . But what I really love is the details and esthetic of the place! oh I am so jealous of your beer tower sooo jealous .

Hipster hell although the people watching here is amusing. Five Leaves' interior is cute but cramped so we always sit outside which is essentially sitting on the corner of a busy Williamsburgh/Greenpoint intersection but the food pretty much makes up for it. This whole New York couture burger thing that's been going on for a few years is getting out of hand and frankly I don't think Five Leaves' is so special. What is damn special are their delicious Thai inspired mussels (oh that broth!), the BLAT (bacon, lettuce, avocado and tomato sandwhich) as well as some hearty yet delicate salads and their delightful cocktail menu. And for all it's hipster appeal the wait staff is super friendly and cool (prolly the Aussie influence). It's a neighborhood joint for us and we hit it  for a reliable, leisurely and luxe lunch at least once a month.

I've been here a couple times for brunch. After an hour wait, then another hour for our food, it was a major disappointment. Even though I was starving and could have ate anything at that point, the food still tasted mediocre. I want to like this place because it is cute and the drinks are good. But the food is just below standards and overpriced. Not worth your time. Boo.
No comment

Mmm, the ricotta pancakes were delish! I can't wait to eat here again when it gets warmer, because I know sitting out on the sidewalk would be divine. I went here on a Friday morning and it was packed.....this says something about the place. Worth a wait, and you'll leave happy.

I love the food. Brunch is fantastic... great iced coffee, the eggs with sauteed kale or mushrooms or bacon... yum! Even better though, the ricotta pancakes. Best pancakes I have ever had, hands down. I would give this place five stars, but I hate the wait and I hate practically sitting on my neighbor's lap. The food is worth it, though!
No comment

This must be one of the most overrated restaurants in the hood. It's just where hipsters go to dress up and look important. The food was ok but had very little substance, it's  not even in my top 10 places to go in the hood. It's pretentious yuppie food, you'd be better served going to Egg for brunch for truly delicious food. The wait for brunch here is absolutely RIDICULOUS, and then you sit down and get served pretty bland fare. This place is ALL HYPE, don't waste your money just to be seen here.

Quality joint. Place was crowded and there really isn't anywhere to wait but the hostess managed to seat us much faster than she originally said. Food was delicious --we shared the delicious kale salad and then I had a wonderful stuffed squid special and the fries. I wish it were a little roomier but that is my only complaint, and in nice weather the outdoor tables take some of the spillover. Last time I was there ate at the sweet romantic banquette in the back. I'd come more often if I lived closer by.

I had a great lamb dinner here, the coffee is fantastic. They serve stumptown coffee. Also had a decent beer called six points, not amazing tho. Very cute restaurant. I had meant to check this place out due to a website I found with 20 best places to eat in Brooklyn but accidentally ended up here anyway.

This is actually as good as it gets. The wait is killer... the fact that everyone keeps waiting several years down the road is a statement in itself. I've been coming to Five Leaves for about 4 years. The food is 100% every time. I must have had about 80 brunches and a few dozen dinners here and I've never had a miss, NEVER in nearly one hundred meals. And the staff is amazingly professional, hip and beautiful but still extremely friendly. The ricotta pancakes can't be passed up (order for the table to share on top of your meals) and the yogurt is shockingly large with the best assortment of fruit I've had anywhere. Their eggs are amazing so big brekkie if you're hungry or the sage panini for light days... and always get a side of avocado, so fresh and perfectly ripe - I'm from Cali so I know. They make it all look so easy, I always leave wanting to come right back :)

I just love this place. I visited from LA last year, stayed nearby .... This year I had to come back and traveled from manhattan just for brunch.... And it did not disappoint.! I had the egg sandwich with amazing tasty tomato jam, we shared pancakes loaded with fresh fruit....to die for!..., side of thick perfectly cooked bacon... My wife had the the big breakie with fried tomatoes and fries. All perfect. ...and did I mention the fab coffee!
No comment
Usually you have to wait, the price is reasonable but not cheap and the food quiet amazing. Fav: rosewater pavlova for dessert
No comment

Love. Truffle fries, please. Sometimes, only this burger will do, nothing else, nowhere else. Stumptown coffee, outdoor seating. Tight space but it's okay for the most part. Good selection of booze. Can't ask for much more. Does get crowded, of course.
No comment

This is the place where the phrase hipster service was invented. 30 minutes for a raw hamburger you ordered medium? I don't see what all of the fuss is about. And if you like a nice 40 degree breeze from the coffee to go window then you'll love this place.

Absolutely love this place.  Love the truffle fries.  Love that they play only vinyl.  Love the coffee.  Love the seasonal cocktails.  Love the decor, love the block, love the flowers on the table and the candles in the bathroom.  Servers are always super sweet and attentive even if there is a really long wait.  There are only a few vegetarian entrees but honestly get a salad and the truffle fries and you will be stuffed full of deliciousness.  The breakfast is to die for!!

Stopped for brunch after running errands in the neighborhood. Surprisingly crowded and overheard 40-45min wait for seating inside...on a weekday! Over the weekend, I can understand, but seems a little ridic that folks were willing to wait on a Monday. No wait for seating outdoors and surprisingly warm sitting outside in the sun. Ordered the ricotta pancakes which were delicious. Great portion sizes as I people-watched other's orders waiting for my second cup of coffee. No free refills sadly...and service was a bit slow, but overall good food and I would return.
No comment
No comment
No comment
No comment

Went there on Oscar night. Good atmosphere. Very good cocktails! Ordered two appetizer specials and a side of truffle fries. Kale-Chorizo soup special was unbelievably bland; the prawns (special) were smothered in pepper (it must have been an accident, seriously) and at least 5-6 other ingredients/competing flavors; the truffle fries...the one dish that I had hoped would save the evening, turned out to be stale. I think it'll be a while before I go there again.

Wow this place rocks. The service is great and quick(thursday lunchtime, I am sure weekends are mobbed) Food was great, had hanger steak sandwich which was cooked perfect. I will be going back in evening to try dinner options(any suggestions?)

It's hard not to give five stars for the two things on the menu that send me into rapture every time I get the chance to eat here: truffle fries and home made ricotta.  For some reason the Five Leaves burger is more than a little sub-par, all the slippery pickles and egg just sliding around everywhere on the plate and overpowering the sandwich.  Other than that, its a fantastic menu, a small menu but a fine menu.  The food here is good, and the atmosphere is good, and even though I had a full drink spilled on my lap once while squeezed into the corner table by the kitchen, I don't mind because the TRUFFLE FRIES!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

Thank you for having great coffee available via a take out window for my morning needs.  Thank you for creating the best breakfast sandwich and thank you for a great drink menu and delicious oysters in the evening.  I think you have created a great restaurant on a great corner in Williamsburg.  I love sitting outside in the summer and having lunch while watching everyone walk by.  I love your dinner specials and I think I love you!

I think its a little overpriced and the food is alright. I tried the beet and blood orange salad but was immediately disappointed. The arugula topped with goats milk yogurt tasted bitter, unpleasant and just wrong. The celery root mash was amazing though and I'd go back just for that. It is very cute and charming inside.
No comment
No comment
No comment
No comment
No comment

I have never visited Five Leaves and had an experience that was less than lovely. The food is delicious, the terrific-to-look-at staff is smiley and kind, and they were so nice to my little dog. My favorite place in the neighborhood.
No comment
No comment

Great food.  Steak is unbelievably yummy.  Unfortunately the sound level in the evening is so loud you literally cannot speak across the table and getting your order understood to the server who is leaning over towards your ear is a challenge.  5 stars unreservedly if you don't need to talk and are willing to wear earplugs.

I just visited NYC for the first time, I live in Austin TX. I went to quite a few restaurants and this one was the bestttttt. There was a 45min-1hr wait, which is quite a while, however the amazing hostess said she would text me when the table was ready. What? thats awesome! haha. so we went to a bar to get a beer and the wait went by quickly and I received the text and we went back to the restaurant and were seated. The atmosphere here is just so great. Its busy but still intimate. I had a burger and fries which was amazing. We also shared some oysters which were fantastic. Next time I go to NY this place will be #1 on my list to go back to.

Darling delicious place.  Williamsburg has Manhattan trumped for innovative fresh food in atmospheric places. Yet another awesome restaurant here.  I tried their Alaska cocktail and really enjoyed its herbal ginniness, perfect for summer.  We demolished the fried oysters and devils on horseback. The irony of dates, a staple Middle Eastern food, wrapped in bacon, not lost on me every time I enjoy them. Opposites attract and compliment. Savory sweet.  Ying yang.  We also had the fried cauliflower which was good, although I'd fantasized about it differently.  I ordered the hanger steak, cooked perfectly to my request.  MP ordered the lamb shepherds pie (in July ?!) and loved it.  We said yes to dessert (!) and had pineapple upside down cake which MP loved.  I'm a bit more hedonistic and basic about my desserts and would have preferred it a little more rustic, less precious.  That said, I savored every bite and will return frequently now that we are in the neighborhood.  It's a fantastic restaurant with great atmosphere.
No comment

We read about Five Leaves while on the west coast, and sought it out on our visit to Brooklyn.  We arrived on a warm Thursday evening around six pm. The outside tables were all filled but there was plenty of room inside.  They played some cool background music (the Youngbloods, jazz, etc).   As our meal progressed, the place began to fill up, and by the time we left it was a packed party vibe.   So, if you like a quieter ambiance, come early!  The service was attentive throughout, though more personal before it got so crowded. While not inexpensive, our food was excellent.  We ordered a grilled fish called dorade, which was succulent and tasty.  Another dish consisting of sautéed ricotta cheese, was also delicious.  The truffle fries were fine, though not necessarily "to die for" as some other reviewers have contended.  The server recommended a Riesling wine, which was just right for us. We had to ask for bread, but once we did it was soft, yet crispy and tasty.  The chocolate pecan tart was a wonderful finish to our meal.  A minor complaint was that we ordered an ice tea and twice asked for refills.  We were unaware we'd be charged for three teas.  I would add a fifth star if you don't mind a crowded party scene as the evening progresses, or if you arrive around 5 pm for dinner while it's still calm and peaceful.

I think it's funny that people are so crazy with reviews.  They've done an amazing job so far and this place is pretty relaxed and the food is good.  The hype is annoying--how about we talk about the living and the amount of effort that has gone into making it work.  The truffle fries are bangin' ($8?  really?) and the brunch egg sandwich is REALLY simple and good---especially if you like sage.  Ricotta pancakes good too. Congrats all around...and kudos for sallying forth with the project.  Someone is smiling from heaven, mate.
Cheap good hamburger! Yum yum;)

I've been here once for dinner and once for brunch (got a burger, moroccan egg scramble, oysters, truffle fries). Overall the food is above average (truffle fries are delicious), the service is good, the music is good. It's a small place and seems to be packed at all hours, so get in early for a table at brunch. I'll probably return at some point to try the pancakes.
No comment

Huge Fan... My wife and I love this place.  It's always a bit too packed for us to try their brunch but we have been here several times for dinner.  The burger is amazing and the bartenders are great.  We came here once just to drink beers and ordered their truffled frites - just a perfect relaxed night.
The hostess  and sever was so rude to our party. The food is great. Dec.12,2014.... Terrible service!!!!

From the outside, the place looks like a typical bar.  Nothing special.  But let me tell you, the food is incredible!  Simply delicious.  Everything was great from appetizer to dessert.  The truffle fries are out of this world!  Excellent food and great service too.  Too bad there's a long wait... it's worth it though.

This cozy place is a great place to grab breakfast. Moderately priced for fresh made, high quality food. We ordered the Moroccan scramble and the ricotta pancakes. Both were delicious. It can get crowded as the place is small, but the food and atmosphere is cute and fitting for the neighborhood. Would definitely come back again.
4- stars for the atmosphere. it's a tiny joint that has NYC feel. dirty martinis were deliciously smooth, mussels in a creamy coconut milk broth as my meal and fried oyster appetizers.
i just wish that had even one vegan option on the menu.  sure, its my choice to be vegan and i dont have to go to this restaurant, but it'd be nice.  its not that hard.
get the ricotta, fig, honey dish, even if none of those are "your thing"
No comment
No comment

This place was on point! A friend took us here for dinner on Sunday night. We waited a long time to get seated but the place was packed. We finally got seated inside and it was pretty snug but had a warm intimate setting - great for a date. The ambiance was chill - lovely music selection - lots of hipsters. Our waitress was awesome and the chef overlooking the orders was pretty hot. Lol. As for the food, the truffle fries is a MUST! You can't go wrong with truffle oil. Also, everyone should try the Flash Fried Oysters with smoked chili and cucumber relish - it was to DIE for! I seriously still can't stop thinking about it. They had a variety of drinks to choose from - I liked the spicy bloody mary - it left a tingly feeling on my lips. I wish I had room for dessert though. Overall, my experience was quite yummy. I'll definitely recommend this place to my friends and come back to try the other dishes in the menu.
No comment
Normal food, really bad service. Not friendly staff. I don't know why it's so popular and has good ratings but I will not go again.

Beyond overrated. Went for brunch last Sunday, but got there at 3:33pm and the brunch menu ends at 3:30 so could only order from the "in between" menu. The food is average and the service is AWFUL. We waited 20 minutes for our drinks. So did the table next to us. When the customer at the table next to us asked where her coffee was the waitress cut her off and in a patronizing tone said "they're making it honey, they're making it." She'd ordered a coffee when she sat down and had already been served her entree before getting her coffee. The mussels are interesting, but not outstanding like they claim. The hostess was so rude and pretended there was a 25 min wait for a table when there were clearly at least 6 tables open or opening up outside then after we stood for five minutes she sat us at the table that she initially insisted we couldn't sit at. This place sucks.
Really amazing menu at good prices. So many delicious vegetable dishes. Really kind and helpful service. cool atmosphere.

What I love about Five Leaves is that the dining experience somehow manages to feel season-appropriate, no matter what time of year. It's the perfect place to seek shelter on a frigid winter evening, huddled close to your companions in the crowded dining room, sipping a fiery hot toddy out of a mason jar and enjoying hearty fare. Come summertime, it's also a great place to grab a juicy burger and sip lemonades on the sidewalk. Though I'm in love with their regular burger (comes with an amazing harissa mayo!) and order it every time, my friends have practically deified the monstrous Five Leaves burger.  The beetroot ravioli is also a favorite.

Probably the best burger in the city in my opinion.  The truffle fries are also outstanding. I just wish the place was a little bigger sometimes the wait on the weekends is pretty long and you have to wait standing outside which is not fun in the winter time.  I do it since the food is awesome.  Ill definitely be going there again.

Consistently great food, efficient wait staff, excellent cocktails at a great price and fantastic atmosphere even during busiest of times. I have yet to have less then stellar experience. Do not go here during busy hours if you aren't prepared to wait for quite some time and definitely try the burger which, in my experience, is the best that Brooklyn has to offer.

Love this place! great interior, and great exterior!! This is Heath Ledgers restaurant. I've only been here for brunch, but on all occasions, the food was good, the service was good and the bloody marys are strong! Definitely a favorite if you're in that part of town.
Gastropub par excellence!  Awesome food and great music.  Well worth the waits.  People watching and flavors on steroids.

a gem within the Greenpoint neighborhood! great burgers, very nice ambiance within a very cozy interior (you get to know your fellow diners pretty well), great service, and decent prices. their truffle fries are a must and if there is a special that piques your interest - definitely go for it! this is a cute location to catch up with a friend or to go on for a mid-week date...then there's a bar around the corner to keep the party going !

Love the place, the good and the ambient. The staff is amazingly friendly and so helpful. All the dishes we ordered were amazing and served so nice! The wait for 7:30pm on Friday was long but totally worth it! I just wished it wasn't so loud sometimes.
Best, most interesting cocktails in Brooklyn. And also the cutest chef in Brooklyn!
Overpriced, oversalted, and just plain old disappointing hipster hangout.  Save yourself the wait, and just go up the street to Brooklyn Label for a much more enjoyable experience.

the shepherd's pie and the signature burger are worth the trip from anywhere in nyc.  the staff is friendly and the atmosphere is lively, yet remarkably chill.  been going here on a weekly basis since it opened and five leaves has yet to disappoint me.  delicious coffee too!

My boyfriend took me to Five Leaves while I was in town this past week, and it was a perfect date night. We arrived there around 8pm on a Friday night, and he let me know that there would likely be a wait, but there was a bar. Indeed, there was a 30 minute wait, but we kept ourselves happy with drinks at the bar. If you don't have patience for tight space, I would say don't go on a weekend, but for me, the ambiance (despite the packed house) was worth it. The specialty drinks were incredible! I suggest the Foxtail. The bar was a bit awkward and cramped, but I would have done that over waiting outside in the cold, for sure. I filled myself up with the INCREDIBLE cheese plate and salad, I was so thankful my boyfriend and I decided to share an entrée, the pork chops. The entire meal was cooked to perfection, but I still can't stop thinking about the cheese. The entire plate was amazing! The entire experience was perfect for a date night on a Friday, and I highly recommend it!

ordering off the somewhat limited menu as a vegetarian was a bit tricky but the four different items myself and my wife shared for dinner were all FANTASTIC!  the mixed greens salad was delish and hefty. the cheese platter with nut bread and roasted fruits, awesome. truffle fries, AWESOME.  beet root ravioli, HOLY CRAP, SO GOOD.  service was fantastic as well :)

This was a friendly warm and cozy cafe with fantastic service.  We all ordered the big breakfast and the bacon was the nicest I have had in a while with perfectly poached eggs.  Coffee was quick to arrive and had a mellow flavour and I love it when you get to enjoy your coffee first then food arrives after.  We are from New Zealand and this was our first morning in New York so thanks for making it such a cool start.
Delicious. Get the burger with fried egg and pineapple, and the truffle fries. When you come back try other stuff.
The ricotta pancakes are more than enough reason to withstand the wait. Always an interesting experience and service is usually on point

I was really excited to try Five Leaves from all the great reviews I was reading.So my colleges and I decided to give it a shot, we went during lunch. I was disappointed at the menu options. Being a vegetarian it's hard to find a restaurant that accommodates. I asked the waitress for some suggestions. she was helpful enough to suggest a salad. So I went with her choice. It took 30min for my salad to arrive and it was extremely salty and not worth the price. I won't be going here anymore.

So, months after my initial review, I did in fact try brunch.  It rocked.  While my dinner experience holds back a star, the brunch added one.  The Moroccan Scramble is legendary, and the Mushroom Toast was awesome.  I am still not rushing back to dinner, but breakfast is a must.  I got there at like 9am on a Sunday (I know, lame) so didn't have to wait really, but normally it is packed so be prepared to wait.

Delicious- we thoroughly enjoyed our breakfast here. Highly recommend the Moroccan eggs- very flavorful! We found the service to be friendly and prompt. We went on a Sunday around 9am and didn't have to wait. Thankfully we were seated at a cute table near the back along the bench so we had ample room. I probably would have rated the experience lower if we had to sit at one of the more cramped tables that lines the wall. The cocktails sounded amazing, but unfortunately we went too early to try them (can't/don't serve alcohol until 11 on Sundays). We look forward to going back next time we're in brooklyn.

I'm reserving the fifth star because of the long wait usually associated with this place in addition to the cramped quarters you're sometimes forced to dine in.  That said, there's a reason for the wait and the cramped quarters because the food here's delicious.  (They certainly don't skimp on the truffle oil and when can you go wrong with truffle oil.)  Great selections for brunch and dinner.  As long as you can plan for and don't mind the wait, then it's a great place to go.  Tip: You can always put your name on the list and then stop by Lokal across the street for a drink at the bar while you wait.

Delicious!  I live around the corner and go at least once a week.  Everything is amazing, from the pancakes to the burger to the salads.  Just typing about the pancakes makes me want to go tomorrow for brunch.  Very cute inside and great crowd of relatively chic, good looking people.  My one complaint is with their take-out coffee.  It tastes good but takes FOREVER.  Expect to wait outside at the window for 5 minutes for a simple iced coffee.  Overall though it's an amazing place and I highly recommend going there.
No comment
Love this place! Mussels, truffle fries, ricotta pancakes. Everything is super yummy!

We love this place since the day it opened in our neighborhood! If you think this place is great, imagine what it was like when it was brand new. The place was perfect perfect perfect it every sense from food, to service, to napkins, to cups, etc. Attention to details has gone down considerably since but it is still very good. Best time to go for dinner is Wen - Sat before 7pm (before the dinner rush) and for brunch on the weekends before 10am or after 1pm.
this place is over-hyped and they don't have AC so have fun dining in a puddle of your own butt sweat
really not exceptionnal - just an OK place
No comment

Great restaurant and bar. Went here on a date, was crowded so we sat at the bar and the bartender was amazing. Apps arrived a little late so we got a free drink. I will come back here again for sure! Great atmosphere and music too!

Have now been for dinner a few times. Food is still quite good, but the scene is maddening and I can't justify the expense when I leave a place that annoyed. And what's with the tables outside in the middle of January? Dear hipsters, I know, it's awesome, you scored a table at Five Leaves during high brunch hour. But you are freaking eating outside in freaking January. I can't take it.

We were really looking forward to coming here but unfortunately the service was terrible and ruined the experience. Our waiter was inattentive and showed no sense of urgency in order to take care of his tables on a busy Saturday afternoon. We watched two couples get seated (at the tables right next to ours), order, eat, pay, and leave before we even got our food. We ordered a second round of drinks while we waited but they never came. After an hour, we asked our waiter if our food was on the way and he seemed annoyed that we asked. A few minutes later the hostess brought our plates out. My Moroccan scramble was cold but the ricotta pancakes were delicious. It took a while for the waiter to bring over the check without saying anything. I completely understand that it may have been a busy afternoon and that this may have been an isolated incident, but our waiter was so inefficient, unapologetic, and lackadaisical, we just left frustrated, unsatisfied, and disappointed.
ive gone here every weekend since it opened. its just perfect. perfect food, perfect ambiance and the servers are very accommodating

Super good food, a swanky burger that doesn't try too hard and tastes good. Cool place and staff without the painfully hip attitude you might expect from this type of place. Great cocktails too, get a Muddled Margret it's gin and something I dunno but they're goood and strong.

Yum ee. I had the artisan cheese plate, the soup of the day, and shared the kale salad with my daughter.  All huge portions and all was fabulous.  My daughter had the house made ricotta - wow!  A little pricey but all well worth it.
Great food at reasonable price. Busy even on a Wednesday night but great atmosphere. Good local beer and a great cocktail menu. Fab atmosphere. Highly recommended
One of my favorites in the city.  Seriously, why leave Greenpoint when you've got a place like this?

Very tasty.  Their breakfast menu is surprisingly vegetarian while their lunch menu is much more meat heavy.  I ended up ordering the sage scrambled egg panini, and added steak to it.  It was good, as was the drink I got (The Sneaky Peat, which was a hot toddie of sorts), but of all of the delicious brunches I tried in the Williamsburg area, it didn't exactly stand out.

Awesome breakfast/lunch spot. Everything we ordered was amazing and everything the people next to us got looked amazing. We need more spots like this in south Brooklyn. Prices are fair. Service was very friendly and only slow due to the high volume of customers. Highly Recommend.

I finally ate brunch here and was really underwhelmed. First of all there are like 5 options..I guess for a place thats known for its brunch I was expecting more and more interesting stuff as well. Inside is extremely loud because dudes are making the loudest ever high brow coffee which you have to shout over ~ i guess people enjoy this charming "atmosphere", also extremely small and awkward navigating to the wc...Now to the food. I ordered the moroccan scramble which looked beautiful but was really difficult to eat because it was in a huge unwieldy pile. There was hardly any merguez in it (i think i literally found 2 little crumbs) and the taste was meh. The avacado was in-edibly lemony, the bread was huge and hard to cut through and the raw pepper garnish on top was too fiery for most people i would think. This is a great example of a huge pet peeve of mine: adorable looking food that is impractical as hell to eat and doesn't even taste good. There did not seem to be much quality control happening. My boyfriend got the "big brekkie" also pretty, his was a much better because it was simple (toast, bacon, eggs). I saw a lot of people eating the ricotta pancakes ..I guess I would stick tho those. I guess all you need in brooklyn is a good reputation.

I went to Five Leaves with a friend the place was packed. My friend and I waited 30-minutes for a table. During the time we waited I watched folks get their food, eat their food and sit around and chat. The pancakes looked amazing but when I got the menu and saw they were ricotta pancakes, they lost their shine. I didn't wanted pancakes with ricotta I was more intrigued when I thought they were straight up pancakes. Anyways, I spotted somebody with an amazing meal so I had the waitress bring me the same. It was good -- eggs, mushrooms and hash browns (two delish fried hockeypucks of amazing potatoes). I also got a coffee. The coffee was quite good I just wished they offered free refills (or at least A free refill). Nope, after I'd drained my coffee, a very nice, funky man who was working hard behind the bar took my mug w/o even asking if I wanted more. Sigh . . . I ALWAYS want to be asked if I want more coffee if I'm dining out. ALWAYS! Nobody really wants just one cup of coffee. Anyways . . . the food was good, the place was nice, the people were uber-funky. If that is what you like Five Leaves is for you.

I used to come here all the time - I really enjoy the brunch and dinner and the amazing cocktails, but you can never get in the place.  So I started ordering food to go since I live very close.  When I ordered take-out last week, a couple bites into the ricotta (one of my fave dishes!) I discovered a giant long hair that was not mine.  Had to throw it out.  I don't think I'll be able to eat food from here ever again.  I was going to give it 1 star, but decided to give 2 since I had some good experiences in the past.
Highly recommend! The truffle fries were amazing, and the five leaves burger was easy the best burger I've ever had.

Yum this place has impeccable food, even at midnight when we went. Absolutely delicious, fresh ingredients, delicately balanced dishes. We had the squash blossoms, baby squash, ricotta on bread, and five leaves burgers. All amazing. Will come back frequently.
No comment
truffle fries, ricotta pancakes, great dark coffee, the list goes on and on and on, but no matter what you are going to order, it tastes great!

Ate with friends on a recent Wednesday night. Good service. They brought us the wrong bottle of wine - it was a Rose when we'd ordered a Sauv Blanc. I blame our table tester for letting her open it despite the color, but nontheless they were good about replacing the bottle with no hassle. They keep water pitchers on the table - a huge plus in my book! Menu was a little too fancy/foreign for our party's tastes (blow fish tail?) and we all got $15 burgers, except the veggie who got a salad and truffle fries. The burgers, fries and salad were all excellent. I regret that we did not order the Devils on Horseback (dates wrapped in bacon served with dijon mustard). I bet they are amazing.
I love this place. Consistently good food. Only problem? They don't take reservations and there is ALWAYS a line!

My, oh f**king my,  the food here is delicious. The first time I came here,I was happy enough to roll out of bed and go to a nearby place with friends on a weekend, but what really made me happy was the granola and fruit...I don't know the exact name on the menu... fresh, delicious granola, greek-style yoghurt, PECANS, and LOTS of fruit (strawberries, blueberries, bananas, oh my!). I absolutely loved it- you also get a lot, so contrary to what granola might sound like, it is filling.  One of my other favorite breakfast/brunch items is the Big Breaky (sp?)-- eggs any style, very yummy hash browns (almost like potato cakes), and a choice of two sides (I usually go for avocado and roasted tomato). It comes with toast and you have the option of adding some grass fed steak slices, which are delectable. As for lunch or dinner, the Five Leaves burger is awesome! Piled high with pineapple and beet, with grassfed beef. Delectable. The kale salad is also delicious. FIve Leaves does get crowded and can pretty loud on weekends, but it's a good place to have breakfast/lunch (or indeed, brunch) or dinner. The outdoor seating area is nice and not as loud. Lovely neighborhood spot.

docking you a star, sadly, b/c service is not what it should be.  or at least service from the waitress assigned to our table could've been better, but thumbs up for the waiter who took pity on us and tried to make up for her obvious, um, inattentiveness (trying to be nice here so not going for words that would fully illustrate our frustration with this particular gal).  i like easy-going and relaxed but not when it translates to barely checking in with/on us and ignoring us when we tried to get her attention.  the food and her fellow server saved the day in the end, but really, please do try to make the dining experience less of a chore.

Visiting from out of town my sister takes me here and said that it was amazing.  Amazing to some degree but defiantly very good.  The wait was ok however if we could have been told we can take a drink out side on the sidewalk that would have been better.  We later noticed that was what some were doing.  The drinks were out standing.  I had the cuban sidecar and a Bees Knees.  Quite yummy.  The food was very good as well.  My sister and I shared the Devils on Horseback, very good.  Next we just had the green salad with croutons.  Great dressing.  Also we had the Kale which I particularly do not care for.  Finally we had the Shepherds Pie which was amazing.  Loved it.  The service was good but very quiet and just ok.  Would go back and not mind waiting for a table.  Max amount of time for wait I would give it 30 minutes.
great place ,always packed but the wait is worth it. excellent burger.and when it s sunny eat outside.
my delicious sage & egg pannini w/soy latte was the perfect post-yoga breakfast.

Fantastic! Amazing food, lively and cozy atmosphere, friendly staff. I never had to wait a long time after ordering. Being relatively new to greenpoint I have to say that this is one of my favorite spots. Highly recommended. Please order the mushroom toast. It will knock your socks off.

Didn't get a chance to try the food here, because we never got waited on.  Eventually we just gave up and left after being ignored, and the staff didn't even notice.  Maybe we'll try again sometime...
my fav. brunch spot before a beautiful bike ride.
was a little afraid of all the hipsters, but the staff was pretty friendly and people watching is always fun. the decor is cute, good coffee and yummy truffle fries.

i love this place for many reasons but I don't see the sense in waiting so long for food when there are a lot of great brunch places around...The big brekkie is yum and everything else I've had has been great but unless i have a lot of time to kill, it's not worth the wait anymore...You should definitley go if you haven't but only on a sunny day so you can soak up the sun while waiting...

These guys make some real good brunch,  on a completely different level than most. It also has that feeling that is the mark of a good restaurant. It's a bit hard to put your finger on but its an complete, cohesive aesthetic experience that has something to do with you forgetting it's a business for a while.

Just got back from a great breakfast at five leaves. This restaurant is close to my apartment so I have been there a few times. This morning I needed a good breakfast with coffee..its getting cold out and there is nothing better than a good and yummy breakfast in a cozy environment with friendly people around. My waitress was very friendly and excellent. The sun was shining, making it feel warm in the restaurant and there were quite a few other people in the room so it was a cozy and warm/relaxed place and perfect to go to on a chilly winter morning. I had the granola and yogurt and fruit with coffee-yum!I have also been here for drinks and dinner at night as well, and everything excellent-the food and staff. The only reason I have to give four stars is because it does get a bit crowded especially at night and is sometimes too busy if you just want a relaxing dinner because it is so crowded.  Other than that I love this warm, cozy and friendly neighborhood establishment:)

I am oh-so-pleased to have a place like Five Leaves in the neighborhood. So far, I have enjoyed the cozy environs of this new little utopia on five occasions, none of which have disappointed me. I've sampled the roasted beet salad, truffle fries, pumpkin and butternut squash soups (served with crusty rustic rolls from the Sullivan Street Bakery), and the bacon wrapped dates. UH, YUM! My beloved recently indulged in the sage scrambled egg sandwich and declared that Five Leaves would be his new haunt. To boot, Five Leaves serves some of the most flavorful and pleasing coffee around. I could easily fritter away an afternoon sipping one of their cappuccinos and noshing on a roll or laze away a winter evening drinking a glass of their temperanillo and nibbling on some fries.  I will say that I have yet to indulge in a full scale dinner adventure at Five Leaves and I am slightly disappointed by the fact that though their beet root ravioli does look interesting, it is the ONLY vegetarian entree on the menu. Will it kill you to offer something other than pasta? And would it kill you to offer two options? Other than this one critique, Five Leaves has my vote as a top notch addition to the hood.

I am honestly giving Five Leaves 4 out of 5 stars because I feel like Yelp will start deleting my reviews if I am giving everyone 5 stars.  This is HANDS DOWN one of my favorite and most frequented restaurants.  It is close to my house and I know most the people who work there (because I am there all the time) and I kinda have this weird obsession with Melbourne and the people who live there, so you know...I'm kinda creepy.  You HAVE to try the five leaves burger, it is messy but incredible.  The grilled pineapple is spot on.  But my 2 favorites are the devils on horseback (dates wrapped in thick bacon) and the skirt steak.  Their steak is always cooked perfectly and the sauce is divine.  And celery root mash?  Get outta town!  Plop down at the bar and stay a while.  Oh, and prepare to wait most of the time.  I am not the only person who loves this place.  I also only rated price on dinner, if you are having a drink or two. Most of the time you can walk away with only spending $20-$30 depending on if you are going for brunch or dinner.
the greatest burger of all time.  period.  cool, comfortable spot.  enjoy.

My friend had been bothering me for over a year to try this place, so I finally did and completely regret not coming sooner.  Saying the food is amazing would be an understatment, I was literally speechless after this experience.  We began with a bottle of very reasonably priced cote du rhone red, which yes was the cheapest on the menu because thats the way it goes, but was just fine and a great way to get our appetites going.  We shared the half dozen oysters which came with 2 great sauces-a garlic chile and some sort of mignonette.  The oysters were fresh and wonderful, and the mignonette sauce which was my favorite was just perfect.  We also shared a simple appetizer of warm bacon wrapped dates with dijon mustard as an accompaniement.  The dates were huge and sweet and paired perfectly with the salty crispy bacon and the dijon cut the richness to really round out this simple yet incredible dish.  What really blew my mind though was the seared scallop appetizer which I had as an entree.  The scallops were sweet and seared to perfection, and were placed upon a bed of black lentils, wonderfully seasoned with a hint of dijon mustard and a serious slice of thick maple smoked bacon. The bacon just fell apart and just sent this dish over the top.  This was by far the best scallop dish that I have ever had in my life and literally left me speechless.  I cant wait to come back for more!

Excellent food. Our new favorite place in the area. The oysters were superb, the lamb and mussels were perfect and everything else that was ordered in our group left a smile on everyone's face. The drink menu is good as well. It's a small place with in and outdoor seating but be prepared to wait. It can get busy, but we got lucky. We had to wait for the rest of our party. After talking to a restaurant employee they said they couldn't hold a table or seat us until our entire party was there (per usual) so we went to grab a drink at a nearby bar. When we got back, as a full group, a table was ready for us. Not sure if they did 'hold' the table or our timing was just perfect, but we were seated promptly. All in all we had a great experience, loved the decor and the food and will be back for more.

Has a great neighborhood vibe. The burger is amazing and comes with an incredible pickle with Janelle C. and I are pretty sure are the spicy McClure's pickles. Great place to sit outside and people watch.

We sat at the Bar, great service and friendly staff. The sage, tomato and egg on bread was creamy, fluffy, and savory. Eggs were airy and cooked just to perfection! Subtle but clean and just the right balance of flavors. My boyfriend got the morracan eggs which was a stronger flavor, great balance if herbs with the egg, highly recommend. Bloody Mary's had a good pour and can't go wrong! All and all was a very satisfying breakfast!

I've dined here 3x in the past two years and enjoyed it each time. The service has been great (less pretentious than it seems like it would be) and the food is seasoned well. I especially enjoyed a tobacco-infused cocktail I had there a few months ago.
Truffle Fries!!! Ahhh soo good!
The pancakes alone are worth the 5-star rating. Best pancakes I've ever had, by far. Can't stop thinking about them. I'd highly recommend them to ANYONE.

Great ambiance, especially during the summer when you can sit outside.  Food is usually very good- contemporary American- delicious, creative salads and fresh, flavorful meats and fishes.  The kale salad is epic and the mussels are pretty good too!  Tip:  when you order, remind them to go easy on the salt or else you will be thirsty for the rest of your life.

truffle fries...best fries i've ever had. devils on horseback were great, but i wouldn't order the octopuse again...seemed to get lost in the sauce..sounded good in theory, but lacked any pop. place is very nice as well.
Great place for brunch and dinner. Perfect for a date, dinner with your parents or drinks with your friends. Ladies this is where all the hot bartenders are!!!

Trendy spot with good but not outstanding American dishes. I'd definitely come here again though. The atmosphere is lively and fun. It's a nice place to stop by with a small group for some conversation and standard American cuisine with an occasional vegan twist for some menu choices. For example, although not vegan, I enjoyed a large juicy burger made from free-range beef raised on a vegetarian diet, and you could certainly taste the difference. Obvious cons: service was a tad mediocre (waitress never seemed to be near and the food took too long), the place can get uncomfortably crowded, and some dishes are just, well, okay. But the pros do outweigh the cons, so I'll be back.

my wife and I have been here on numerous occasions. I am new to yelp so I'm making up for lost time. Raviolis with fois gras, excellent. Fresh oysters were great, and our knowlegable server steered us towards really complimentary wine selectons. Over all experience was great.

We waited 45 minutes for a cheese platter and tuna tar tar.  The place wasn't even packed, I'd say about tables filled.  Lamb not cooked- was still raw.  Chicken had not flavor.  It tasted like they went to the back, killed a chicken and threw it in the oven.  Suppose to come w/ eggplant puree- it did!  About 1/2 a TEASPOON of it!  Then they forgot my broccoli rabe- it came out- bitter, bitter bitter.  I couldn't eat it.  Not sure why so many people go there, maybe it's for the overpriced drinks bec it's not for the food!
Came here for brunch  Great food! Great price! Delicious almond croissant!  Only draw back is the long wait and small place.

Had a dinner for two here and the food was amazingly delicious! So glad that we decided to try something new. I took off one star because the waiter was a little bit of a dickwad (not attentive)  but lucky for him the food was outstanding..

I've been to Five Leaves several times and have always had a great experience here.  Even Sunday brunch (when I had to wait for a table for about 20-30 mins and had a drink at their bar across the street)! Consistently delicious food.  Love the black kale salad, bacon wrapped dates, BLAT with egg, and lamb they had a while back.

Lets just start by saying there must have been something funny in the water because the waitress was unusually friendly!!!! As an aspiring restauranteur in new york city i am always surprised to find an establishment where genuine hospitality is practiced. I went there on a date expecting mediocre service from some hipster in skinny jeans. BOY WAS I WRONG! Our server ( gorgeous blonde with a harmonica necklace) recommended the ricotta for first course and the pork chops. It was as though my palate had experienced something like never before. It made me forget that though extremely attractive, my date was quite boring.  Because of my experience at Five Leaves i am happy to say that i will most definitely be returning with more interesting and attractive men! P.S. Try the Moscow Mule! It's fabulous!

Love love love Five Leaves. Great early in the morning for coffee/breakfast and in the evening for dinner. Everyone who works there is super friendly and the place is beautiful. Some of my favorite things to get are: the Sticky Date Pudding , Beet Ravioli and the Fried Oysters. So happy to have found it!
Two words: Hanger Steak.  I liked it so much I told the head chef in person.  That man understands meat!
Loved everything from the delicious organic food to the decor to the very friendly owner. It felt like a neighborhood place with just an extra touch of class.
The food is wonderful, the place is cute, they play records on the bar, and they have delicious cocktails.
No comment

Hands down the best brunch and burger place in Williamsburg. I can honestly come here every single weekend for the Moroccan Scramble or Ricotta Pancakes and, of course, the Truffle Fries. YUM! The owners are sweet, hospitable, and accommodating  and the of the waiters are welcoming and funny. i, however, had an unpleasant experience with a female maitre d' who was flat out rude and nasty. Sometimes you get stuck with a kooky waitress that has no idea what she talking about, but you honestly can't go wrong with anything on the menu. Treat yourself to dessert :)

Food and coffee is delicious, but I will NEVER return. The service here is horrible.  This is beyond the typical aloof Williamsburg.  I ordered a cup of coffee to go and had the milk thrown at me, the sugar slammed down on the bar.  There are plenty of places to get good food in Williamsburg.  This is not worth the service.
No comment

I had been to 5 leaves one time prior to going the last time.  The place is tiny and can get really crowded.  The last time I went I was meeting a friend there and decided to go early to have a drink.  Well I walked in, found the last seat at the bar.  Mind you there are only about 6 -8 seats there.  And then waited and waited and waited...the bartender did not even know I existed.  So I left..I guess if you are not a regular or a hipster forget about getting served.  Oh well there are plenty of other places to go.
Tiny little place, one bathroom stall, but AMAZING food.  The brussel sprouts were the best Ive ever had.  My duck comfit risotto was divine, and great service to boot!

i moved to brooklyn from sydney, australia about 10 months ago and i can honestly say this place is my FAVOURITE cafe in new york... and i know good food, i have been to a TON  of cafes in manhattan and brooklyn and nothing really deserves a 5 star rating quite like 5 Leaves. I NEVER write reviews but i love this place so much, I had to write it a killer review.. i mean , the ricotta pancakes, truffle fries, moroccan scramble... EVERYTHING here RULES! bloody marys are great here and the staff are super nice and chilled... they are great at their job and add to the overall experience here for sure.. make sure you go here! you will probably have to wait a short while to be seated cause everyone is wanting a seat! but its WELL worth it! i promise you will be returning back like I have ever since i went for the first time, this place is super special for sure..

I recently moved to Brooklyn from LA and my friends insisted that I try this place for brunch. After a lengthy wait we were seated outside, after some wait we got our drinks and food. It was average for the price, I would say. The menu is actually pretty limited and I had to settle on the Moroccan Scramble which while adventurous, didn't actually come out well as a breakfast dish- I found it overwhelming. I had some of my friend's truffle fries which were tasty but certainly not the best I've had. All in all I'd say this place relies heavily on the Heath Ledger hype and didn't wow me in the slightest.

Have been here a few times for dinner and I have loved it every time! The food is delicious and the menu has a varied selection. The service is great as well. The only downside of this place is that it is pretty small so it can get a little crowded and loud...but this won't stop be from coming back! Love!

I want to give them a better review because the food is seriously so amazing, but I just don't like the clientele.  Am I a dick for saying that?  It's like the atmosphere that Louis C.K. describes when he talks about trendy coffee shops.  Unbelievable food though, seriously!

Kale salad - delicious.  Moroccan Scramble - delicious.  Pancakes - according to husband, delicious.  Granola - delicious.  Hamburger (regular, not the Five Leaves special one) - very good.  Some kind of trout for dinner -- good but not great. The wait for a table - starting to become a deterrent.  Tables - too close together and too small -something falls off our table almost every single time.  Ambiance -  not particularly relaxing - you need to be in the mood for a lot of togetherness.
I love this place. I crave the burger and seem to order it every time i come here, i cant help it its just so good! Also have amazing fries with truffle oil- yum!

food is realy tasty and worth 5 stars.  one of the best pancakes and tasty scrambled eggs. the only complain i have: the place  is very busy and hectic. it is not a place to relax over  a cup pf cafe and a sunday brunch. way to crowded. would be much more enjoyable if cut some 2-3 tables.

Shock health department CLOSE this restaurant by 42 points,live mice,smoking in the kitchen,shame a very well attended restaurant and can not afford a decent cleaning ???? disgusting eaten there many times but never more !!!! Check out ABC Eat !!!!!
The burger was amazing.  Everything is very healthy.  I hear it is great for brunch; the lunch menu is a little small but everything is good.  Can't wait to go back!

The food at Five Leaves is good, but my problem is with the service.  I have been twice and once the service was fine, but the second time I came for brunch and had the worst service I have had in years.  The wait staff neglected to get us menus and even when our waitress stopped by about drink orders she didn't glace down to notice we were menu-less.  Then they brought us the wrong drinks and later they brought us the wrong food.  It took forever to get anyone to get us the check.  And the icing on the cake (though not anyone on the staff's fault) is that the bench on the wall has heaters underneath it and the seats turn into a sauna.  Both times I was there I was sweating by the time I finished my meals.  I may return, but it won't be until the heat is turned off.

Can one review white hot Williamsburg hangout, Five Leaves without using the dreaded 'H' word?  We can if we dance around it, say to the sounds of the Dirty Projectors in our skinny jeans, beards and flannel shirts, with our fixed-gear bikes secured nearby.  Delicious diner/bistro food with gourmet flair, this is Nu-Brooklyn cuisine at its finest.  Serves cocktails so terrific they'll knock your Uggs off.

I was taking a trip to the McCarren Park for my soccer game with a couple of friends, when I saw this restaurant nearby- (between Lorimer St & Nassau Ave) called Five Leaves. When I walked by, a scent of ricotta pancakes was in the air, compiled with banana, and a pile of berries. It looks as good as it sounds. I would say the coffee part is a little overpriced but the breakfast is a must. So I decided to try these ricotta pancakes. They came with a mound of honeycomb butter, toppled with berries, and a whole banana. These amazing pancakes filled me up quickly, and the texture was fluffy and soft. I highly recommend this place, just come before noon and you won't have to wait like a half-an hour for a table. I would also have to say that the exterior view is amazing. Also if you get the chance, definitely try the truffle fries. They are crispy and brown on the outside with softness bundled on the inside. And they aren't even that greasy, like McDonald's or any other restaurants'.

amazing service and great food. I was told i had to get the five leaves burger and it was great-  even had a fried egg on top of it!! i'd never had anything like that before. A wonderful brooklyn spot to visit on my trip to nyc. I just wish it was easier to get a table:)

Sitting in the sunshine with a cup of lemon and ginger tea and a huge stack of beautiful pancakes in front of me laden with fruit and maple syrup is my idea of pure heaven, will come back here for sure!!
Yes, the place is a caricature of hipsterdom, but the coffee is excellent and the pancakes are rich, decadent and delicious.

Very beautiful place.  Nice for a beer or coffee.  I was very disappointed when I had dinner there though.  There were three of us and everyone's was really bad.  New York has become one of the hardest places in the world to find a bad meal, but low and behold, we found one here.  My chicken was awful, it tasted like Purdue, cooked in a public school cafeteria.  The risotto sucked, it was bland.  There was no love put into any of this cooking and the ingredients tasted like they were coming from Sysco's institutional division.  My girlfriend's trout was watery and tasteless.  It has that gross earthy taste that makes you know it is from a very industrial fish farm.  They even couldn't nail pub fair.  The shepards pie tasted like 5 day old lamb curry from an Indian Restaurant in Uraguay or something, with frozen mashed potatoes on top.  Such a shame as it looks very cool.  Also way over priced.  Unless they get there act together and start using god ingredients and get a chef who can cook, they are fucked.

the atmosphere is wonderful and has an industrial, yet comfortable feel to it, though it would be nice if it were a bit bigger, but hey, it's really cute. our waitress was really nice and extremely understanding. the lights were especially adorable and hip. but the food. i shared the home-made ricotta and the ricotta pancakes with my friend. the pancakes were really fluffy and good. it had an entire banana with blueberries and honey butter. the honey butter was SO good. but the ricotta! home made ricotta with honeycomb, sage, sea salt and figs came with delicious fruit bread was absolutely heavenly. the slightly creamy ricotta and savory sea salt combination with the aromatic scent of the sage. oh my yum. my other friends got the BLAT which was okay, though i only had a bite. i am definitely going again.
typical tiny, hipster hipster restaurant. the food is sooo tasty - haven't ever had brunch here, but would love to try! i bet it's super packed even then.

I am a huge fan of Five Leaves.  I'm sure people will think I am crazy, but I firmly believe that they have the best burger in NYC.  And I have had many, trust me. All their food is really, really good though.  Even when I don't order their burger--which is rare, but happens occasionally--I am not disappointed!  I have always had great, attentive, accommodating, fun service there.  Also, love love love their cocktails and wine list.  It's a perfect date place in that it has a sexy, romantic vibe that makes you want to sit, talk, have another cocktail, and soak up the low lighting, but it is also casual and completely unpretentious.  I like it for brunch but I LOVE it for dinner.  I would give it five stars except that, yes, the waits can be prohibitive and it is pretty pricy.  I have had a number of gasps at the bill at the end of my nights there, though part of it is always that I want to stay a little longer so I get another drink or some dessert to justify it!  I highly recommend.

when you've got a craving for truffle fries this place totally hits the spot. it is cozy but everyone is very nice and the food is kind of amazing. i ate there when it first opened and as mentioned it was hot to the point of distraction. now they have that under control and the experience is lovely. i'm particularly partial to their small plates. despite the tastiness, it feels slightly over-priced and i wish that they would add more cocktails to their drink menu.

We found Five Leaves whilst exploring Williamsburg.  Judging by the crowd spilling out onto the street and the look of the burgers and salads, we thought we'd hit on an absolute winner for food.  After  a 30 minute wait, we were finally seated.  I ordered the house made ricotta and His Lordship ordered the grilled swordfish on pumpernickel and a side of fries..  Big mistake!  We should have stayed with the burgers.  The house made ricotta comprised of a bowl of watery, salty ricotta, 3 bitter figs with the honeycomb, olive oil and thyme battling out for taste supremacy.  The grilled swordfish fared no better.  It was basically a cold  fish sandwich with beetroot dip. The fries never arrived.  We both managed to swallow a few spoonfuls and drown our sorrows in our drinks.  The waitress was astonished as to why we hadn't finished our meals. Not wanting to be obnoxious and cause a scene, I had hoped the look on my face relayed my disgust.  We didn't even bother with the missing fries. The waiting staff were hovering, waiting for us to vacate our table for the next guests, so we cut our losses and left.  I would rate that meal as the one of the worst I've had the misfortune of having.  Note to chef:  Drain the Ricotta! Taste your own food!

I've eaten here half a dozen times and can't deny that some of their dishes are quite tasty.  Unfortunately, if you also value service and fair pricing, look elsewhere.  The staff has been spoiled by the high demand (there is generally a long wait), and therefore you will find them impatient and unaccommodating.  We went there for brunch at 2:30pm, and were told there was a 1-hour wait.  We put our name in, followed by a 4-person party behind us.  After an hour, we were seated.  The 4-person party was already at the table next to us enjoying the famous pancakes and eggs we had eagerly awaited.  The waitress then handed us a lunch menu and informed us that we could no longer order brunch, which ended at 3:30 (it was 3:35).  We asked politely if they could just slip an order in as we'd waited an hour for brunch, but they tersely refused and recommended the restaurant across the street (where we ended up going and having a delicious, and more reasonably priced, meal).  If you like 6-oz cappuccinos that cost almost $4, and rude management, this is the place for you

As if this place is not busy as it is.  But, hey, they deserve the 5 stars.  I come here most often for brunch.  But have also come at other times of the day too.  The wait is very long on weekends from morning to afternoon with oodles of people spilling onto the nearby sidewalk.  The service is usually good.  The guy that keeps track of the table wait list is friendly and attentive.  Host, manager, part owner? Not sure who he is, but he has an amazing memory and always remembers you and your position in the line up to get a table.  The staff, for the most part, are upbeat, attentive and non pretentious.  The food is consistent and flavorful.  I like pretty much everything I have ordered here.  The only exceptions to that would be the ricotta appetizer, not bad but sort of bland.  Also the sage, egg breakfast sandwich was not remarkable.  The burger on the other hand is remarkable.  Delicious and I love it with the truffle fries.  Five Leave's truffle fries are like small slivers of greasy crack for me, and I almost didn't try them because I hate mushrooms!  I also really like the baked beans with eggs and toast a lot, but with that burger on the menu it makes it really hard for me to order anything else.  I always promise myself that next time I will try the pancakes because they look really good.  It's also nice to come here on cold winter nights to sit and drink wine with someone on the butt warming benches!
No comment
No comment
No comment
No comment

Had to try this new spot after hearing so many good things. Have no regrets ! I wasn't able to stay for it but apparently the restaurant converts to karaoke bar at 11pm. As for the food I'd recommend the salad, the croquetas, the chicken and swordfish skewers, and Korean fried chicken. The beef tartare was a little salty for my likings but still good. It's a tapas style restaurant so everything is meant to be shared. Our waitress helped us narrow down our order to fit out palette. Liked it a lot!

The innovative dishes here are worth the visit! We sat at the bar on a Friday night, it was lively but we did not feel crowded in. We ordered the gem salad, the lamb neck noodles, an order of chicken + beef skewers (2 per order), and the grande fries. All super tasty. However, I would say the drawback here is that the service is lackluster. Our order except for the noodles came all at once. There needs to be greater consideration of pacing of courses especially for those with limited room at the bar. We felt rushed to eat all of our food while it's hot. Additionally, our plates were not cleared in a timely manner. We enjoyed the skewers but $15 for two skewers with no accompaniments is pricey. The food is great and the restaurant is new so I hope they are able to iron out some of these issues otherwise I would be leaning toward 3 stars next time.

What a fun and delicious dinner! We ordered the Little Gem, Beef Tartare, Braised Lamb Noodles and the Fried Skate Wing on a cold Thursday night. Everything was so good but the fried skate is NOT TO BE MISSED!  The outside is crispy and crunchy, the meat was heafty yet light and broke apart like crab meat. It was just ::chefs kiss:: phenomenal. We both raved about how perfect that dish was.  We had a 730 pm dinner and didn't realize they had karaoke after. The staff were wonderful performers and made us feel so comfortable. Can't wait to visit again!

One of the best meals I've had this year. The gem salad, chilled mussels, and charred cabbage were all standouts, but every single thing that hit the table was interesting and, more importantly, delicious. I will be back over and over again.

Honestly had one of the best meals that I've had in months! We got the Little Gem salad which instantly cured my hangover, the ceviche that was mouth watering, and then fried chicken which reminded me of coconut shrimp in the best way possible. And the servers were all hot and so nice & attentive! what a dream boat of a restaurant
I had the beef tartare and chicken thigh skewers. Both were excellent. It was tough to choose as a lot of the menu looked good to me. Will definitely be back.
No comment
Great ambiance, and even better food! Can't go wrong with anything on the menu. Gem salad is a must.

celebrated my partner's birthday here with a big party. couldn't be more thankful to the staff. the food was delicious, the bar was great, and the ambiance really upbeat. we sang karaoke after dinner with the entire place. don't come here if you don't like good food and fun
this spot was decent. definitely get the fried chicken and scallop crudo. gem salad was too creamy for us. also get the regular fries with the sauce on the side not on top.
We ordered almost everything on the menu in a group and every dish was delicious. Highly recommend the swordfish skewers and chiquita chinita cocktail for a spicy treat.

The food is fabulous! We tried an assortment of dishes and each one was delicious. The Swordfish was tender and just a bit spicy that left me wanting more. The fried chicken was some of the best I've ever had. The cabbage was absolutely bursting with flavor. Everything was truly delicious but my favorite, if I had to pick, would be the Wagyu Steak! So tender and the flavor was pure heaven

One of the more elevated speakeasy experiences I've had in a while. Crowd felt more New York than touristy, the music playlist added to the ambience. Cocktails were strong and the space itself was inviting without feeling stuffy. I wouldn't come here for a full dinner but definitely a pre or post dinner drink.

1 star for the service and 2 for the food. This place is not worth the hype whatsoever. Not only did my server forget to ever bring my my espresso martini but she also brought out 2 burgers when I only ordered one. I used to work in the industry, I get it, servers get busy - the restaurant was half full. I typically would say something in person rather than writing a review but no one ever came back after dropping the check. As for the food, the burger is good enough, but not for $30. Honestly shake shack, 7th street, and Gotham are much better if you're looking for a good smash burger.

This is my favorite speakeasy in NYC. From the staff to the music to the drinks. They knock it out of the park. I've been able to get a table and a seat at the bar without a reservation, but this spot quickly fills up. I usually go with one of the Mezcal cocktails but have also had the bartenders come up with something of me! If you're looking for a sexy, chic spot for cocktails or a date - this is it.

I came here with a friend for some late night drinks. The  entrance/bar area was tightly packed, but once we got to the dining area it was more spacious. It's a pretty place with red velvet chairs, dim lighting, and a diverse range of  music to please everyone. The kitchen closed at 11 so we couldn't get any food. We didn't stay long since we were in search of food, but we enjoyed the time we spent there. Would come again.

Had the most awful experience at DND this evening. Majority of the staff was extremely rude and required us to order food at our table, despite seating us 45 minutes after our reservation and not requiring any other table to order food. When I raised this point to the servers, they basically told us to go f** ourselves, and continued to charge us a nice 20% tip. Needless to say, we will not be returning, and I highly recommend taking your business to Art Bar or Bathtub Gin instead.

Immaculate vibes here. Definitely a sexy, sultry spot that would be perfect for a date. I was able to get a seat at the bar without a reservation but it was pretty poppin' so if you plan ahead it's probably a good idea to have a reservation. Interesting cocktail list with somthing for everyone. I enjoyed my mezcal based drink "pero like, mejor" which was pretty strong but smooth. Didn't get to try any of the food but I'd be interested in coming back. Would recommend!

Stumbled upon this establishment the other evening with a coworker of mine and we were completely blown away be how incredibly sophisticated yet swanky this discreet establishment was. We even walked right past it originally. Definitely an amazing place to grab a drink after work and unwind. Also, Sofia the bartender was top-notch and made me two delicious fruit cocktails, that I'm already craving again

The bouncer was rude and selective with who he let in. They would not let the rest of our party in, even though we were accounted for in the guest count for the table that was already seated, but let another party in that was right behind us. Others in our same party were able to enter without an issue. Sad because I really wanted to support this busy. I will not return.

My friend Ali told me about this place and I am willing to try anything it's in the hart of west village . I guess it was a basement of a house before  I went with 2 friends and we order a 2Godiva martini  #horrible drinks  the attitude of the stuff working there is  I am to cool to serve youthen one of the Manager with the brown jacket  (men) Be a little bit more polite to your customer  if you can't do that go back to do retail and learn to deal with peoples  not a place I will recommend

column3: Upper West Side, New York, NY
column6: Amazing atmosphere, drinks and service! This is the perfect spot for a date or romantic occasion.

Racist treatment at the door, they let two white guys walk in with no issues or questions. When I looked to walk in I (a black man)was told they are at capacity and had to wait for people to leave. I waited for 10 mins alone in the cold, watched 8 people leave and was still not allowed to enter. Sad part is that it was a black door man...

Amazing gem of a place! Tucked away downstairs, the ambiance is low light, candles, flowers and a fantastic mix of new & 90's music. Not only the ambiance, the food is delicious & the service is friendly. Our party ordered a little of everything and each plate was cleaned. Will definitely be back & will highly recommend!

Came here with a group of friends and had PHENOMENAL food and service... entrance is a bit hidden but once you're in, it's packed in the front with good vibes and delicious drinks, while in the back you have a separate, well managed aesthetically seated area for reservations (plan ahead if possible and make reservations!!!). The drinks were consistent and tasty (not TOO strong nor weak) and the staff is more than friendly - they offered recommendations (tuna crispy treats & lemon pepper mala wings!!! Amazing!!) the owner and chef even came out to our table to check in with us to see how we were doing! It was a Saturday night and so this was pretty unexpected - the chef also was on masterchef so it comes to no surprise that great food comes with a chef who engages with the patrons 1v1! Overall I would most definitely recommend this speakeasy - nails everything from service/food/drinks/ambiance!
Overpriced with terrible service. Super disappointed with the experience and will honestly never go again.

The GM was very rude and combative. He rolled his eyes at our party as well as others.. The hostess was extremely sweet and helpful.. As someone who has worked in the industry I found this GM's behavior unprofessional and unnecessary.

Phenomenal night at DND. Des the bartender in the front room is absolutely fantastic. Super on point with drinks and overall great energy. You must get the smash burger and make sure you don't share it with anyone like I did. I almost ordered another. Also yes to the tuna crispy starter. The one thing that threw me off was the different rooms having different vibes. We went right before sundown so the green room was super bright with light. But by the time the sunset, the vibe was great through out the restaurant. Also funny that they were playing such good music and I told my bf that I wished they would crank the vol maybe 1-2 more notches to really get the vibe up and clearly someone knew what I was wanting and it was turned up. All staff interacted with were friendly, warm, and had great fits on. I love it when I'm at a restaurant and can't tell if it's staff or patrons haha. Can't wait to go back again soon.

Utterly superb. Just superb. The kale salad and the ceviche were among the best I have ever had. The texture and the subtle layering a flavor in both dishes indicates a true maestro at work. The setting is sumptuous and the staff are beyond professional and engaging. A perfect evening.
Poor service - since originally going here I have had a poor experience liaising with the staff. I don't recommend going here.
Chef Josh is the #1 young chef in all of downtown Manhattan. He's putting out really impressive food. Drinks are solid. Would recommend.
Awesome decor, great service, very cool drinks. All around cool, low-key swanky vibes.

We love this place. The whole menu is amazing and have been coming for the last 2 years. Service is always curated and the food is always great. Never had a bad dish here. Their cocktails are also very well balanced and the ambiance is modern, without being pretentious. Definitely a place to keep coming over and over.

Solid spot in ktown with a creative take. The fried chicken comes in a whole chicken, and the pork shank is super soft (although I think it was better in the past). The soups have always been super flavorful and tasty, and the vibe in the restaurant is great. Do note that it gets very busy though and you will have to leave after an hour and 45.

Cute date night spot that's serves Korean food with a modern twist. We got the steak tartare (yukhoe), soy garlic wings, and kimchi fried rice with skirt steak and truffle fries (not pictured). Love love love this place. If you ever come here, make sure you make a reservation as it gets really busy!

You gotta love this place for what it is, a swanky bar for drinks and socializing. The food is lacking, especially the dishes that aren't Korean, but the drinks are superb and the bartenders are beyond attentive. They take care of you like a baby, with a napkin when you need it, a warning that the dish is hot or a change of plates. They always have their eye on you to make your experience as cozy as possible. If you must eat though, the oysters are fresh and tasty, and the Korean classic chicken wings are the perfect combination of crispy, sweet and spicy. The uni bibimbap sounds exciting but the uni was very bitter and the dish overly oily and lacking in flavor. The gambas dish even more so, if you can imagine.

We ordered French fries ($8), wings ($16), endive and Korean pear salad ($17), oden tang ($28), osamil kimchi fried rice w/ hanger steak ($35), uni bibimbap ($38), and pork shank ($43). The flavor profile for the most of food we ordered was honestly not impressive to me except their pork shank, but their price is just insane.. you can tell the price is high when you look at kimchi fried rice for $25 and oden tang for $28. Their happy hour is 5-7 for drinks, but their last call for the drinks was 6:40pm which I think was too early for the last call. Service was very attentive and quick. Food came out quick as well. Overall, the presentation for the food was nice/instagrammable, but I couldn't give them 5 stars because of the price. Will I come back? Meh... maybe not.

I met up with some friends here and we all shared a few drinks and the pork shank. The drinks were all not to my taste -- either too strong, too bitter, or just off tasting. The pork shank was alright, but for the price definitely not worth it. However, the overall vibe of the place is really nice so maybe they have better options that just haven't been found yet.

After coming across their menu, I knew I had to get dinner here soon. I had a great opportunity to check this place out with friends. I tried my best not to order everything on the menu, everything sounded amazing! Most of the food & beverage items sounded better than they tasted. Cocktails were too light, and too sweet but I love the concept and variety they offer. I didn't see this coming but I really enjoyed their chicken dishes. The wings had great crisp and juicy flavors , and and the Korean Market Fried Chicken. The quality and flavor is all there. The beef tartare had a wonderful spicy umami flavor, but what a minuscule portion. Not going to order the pork shank and uni bibimbap again. The pork shank had a strong boar taint and the sauce it came with was unpalatable but unfortunately I had already mixed it in. The host was friendly but other parts of service was slow.

We had just landed from SF and were looking for a quick bite but what we found was so much more.   All the flavors in each dish knocked out socks off.   We had the Kim chee fried rice and the steak tartar.   Both were well prepared and packed a lunch of flavor.    The frizee salad was perfectly dressed and had just the right amount of sweet and crunch.  Wonderful bar with a great vibe.    We had hit the jackpot!
